(fifthQuint)Rifampicin Explorative PK Study for Tuberculous Meningitis Comparing Oral and Intravenous Preparation.

 Introduction: In a recent clinical trial the investigators have shown that a higher dose of rifampicin administered intravenously (600 mg iv) during the first 2 weeks of treatment is safe and associated with a survival benefit in adults with TB meningitis.

 An oral (rather than iv) dose would help implementation of intensified treatment for TB meningitis.

 However, it is hard to predict what oral dose of rifampicin will result in rifampicin exposures similar to 600 mg iv, due to differences in bio-availability (oral vs.

 iv) and the unpredictable dose-concentration relationship (nonlinear pharmacokinetics of rifampicin).

 Therefore the investigators aim to examine the pharmacokinetic of 2 higher doses of rifampicin (750 mg and 900 mg) given orally, and compare the pharmacokinetic profiles with the result of our previous study using 600 mg rifampicin iv.

